## Why Generics Exist

Before Java 5, collections were raw typed — you'd cast everything manually and get `ClassCastException` at runtime. Generics move type-safety to **compile time**.

```java
// Before generics (pre-Java 5)
List list = new ArrayList();
list.add("hello");
String s = (String) list.get(0); // runtime cast

// With generics
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("hello");
String s = list.get(0); // no cast needed, compile-time safe
```

## Type Erasure

Java generics are implemented via **type erasure** — generic type information exists only at compile time. At runtime, `List<String>` and `List<Integer>` are both just `List`.

### What erasure does:
- Replaces type parameters with their bounds (or `Object` if unbounded)
- Inserts casts where needed
- Generates bridge methods for polymorphism

```java
// Source code
public class Box<T> {
    private T value;
    public T get() { return value; }
}

// After erasure (what bytecode sees)
public class Box {
    private Object value;
    public Object get() { return value; }
}
```

## Wildcards and Bounds

### Upper Bounded: `? extends T`
Use when you want to **read** from a structure. You know items are at least T.

```java
public double sumList(List<? extends Number> list) {
    return list.stream().mapToDouble(Number::doubleValue).sum();
}
```

### Lower Bounded: `? super T`
Use when you want to **write** to a structure. You know items can accept T.

```java
public void addNumbers(List<? super Integer> list) {
    list.add(1);
    list.add(2);
}
```

### Unbounded: `?`
Use when you don't care about the type at all — only need Object methods.

## Bridge Methods

When a class extends a generic type and overrides a method, the compiler generates a **bridge method** to maintain polymorphism after erasure.

```java
class StringBox extends Box<String> {
    @Override
    public String get() { return "hello"; } // your method
}

// Compiler also generates (bridge method):
// public Object get() { return get(); }  // calls String version
```

This is why `getDeclaredMethods()` may return more methods than you wrote.
